'''Moses Cohen Mordecai''' (1804-1888) was an American businessman, politician, and ''[[gabbai|parnas]]'' (synagogue administrator). He was the owner of the Mordecai Steamship Line, which he used to import fruit, sugar, tobacco, and coffee. He also served as a member of the [[South Carolina Senate]]. He became "the most prominent Jewish Charlestonian of the 1850s and 1860s."<ref name="rosen40"/> During the [[American Civil War]], he supported the [[Confederate States of America]], and his ships were used by the [[Confederate States Navy]]. He retired in Baltimore.

==Early life==
Moses Cohen Mordecai was born on February 19, 1804 in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. 

==Career==
Mordecai owned the Mordecai Steamship Line, which he used to import fruit, sugar, tobacco, and coffee.<ref name="rosen40">Robert N. Rosen, ''[[The Jewish Confederates]]'', Columbia, South Carolina: University of South Carolina Press, 2000, p. 40</ref><ref name="jewishcharleston">[http://www.jewishcharleston.org/page.aspx?id=213491 Jewish Tour of Charleston] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140529183042/http://www.jewishcharleston.org/page.aspx?id=213491 |date=2014-05-29 }}, ''The Jewish Federation of Charleston, South Carolina''</ref> Additionally, he was a co-owner of the ''[[Southern Standard (defunct newspaper)|Southern Standard]]'', a newspaper published in South Carolina from 1851 to 1858.<ref name="rosen40"/> At the same time, he served as a member of the [[South Carolina Senate]].<ref name="rosen40"/><ref name="jewishcharleston"/> His votes reflected his opposition to secession in the 1850s, prior to the [[American Civil War]] of 1861-1865.<ref name="rosen40"/> He used his newspaper to echo this position.<ref name="rosen40"/> Moreover, he was widely seen as a politician representing the merchant class and free trade.<ref name="frankbyrne">Frank Byrne, ''Becoming Bourgeois: Merchant Culture in the South, 1820-1865'', Louisville, Kentucky: University Press of Kentucky, 2006, p. 62 [https://books.google.com/books?id=90ZHraBlhr8C&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=%22Moses+Cohen+Mordecai%22&source=bl&ots=Cw--OlXflM&sig=mHvlqWGCCz74-SkXgzHRx4Vl78k&hl=en&sa=X&ei=23qHU4-GOMyYkgWgjIHIBw&ved=0CCQQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22Moses%20Cohen%20Mordecai%22&f=false]</ref>

According to author Robert N. Rosen, Mordecai became "the most prominent Jewish Charlestonian of the 1850s and 1860s."<ref name="rosen40"/> He served as the ''parnass'', or chief administrative officer, of the [[Congregation Kahal Kadosh Beth Elohim]], a synagogue in Charleston.<ref name="rosen9">Robert N. Rosen, ''The Jewish Confederates'', Columbia, South Carolina: University of South Carolina Press, 2000, p. 9</ref> Overall, he did not suffer from much open antisemitism; however, historians have noted that Senator [[James Henry Hammond]] (1807–1864) privately called him a "miserable Jew" in his diary.<ref name="frankbyrne"/>

During the [[American Civil War]] of 1861-1865, Mordecai decided to change his mind about secession and supported the [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name="preservation">[http://www.preservationsociety.org/program_historicmarkers-Detail.asp?hmID=49 69 Meeting Street: Poyas-Mordecai House] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140529183015/http://www.preservationsociety.org/program_historicmarkers-Detail.asp?hmID=49 |date=2014-05-29 }}, ''Preservation Society of Charleston''</ref> Some of his ships were used by the [[Confederate States Navy]].<ref name="jewishcharleston"/><ref name="rosen47">Robert N. Rosen, ''The Jewish Confederates'', Columbia, South Carolina: University of South Carolina Press, 2000, pp. 46-47</ref> For example, the ''Isabel'', named in honor of his wife, was used to remove Major [[Robert Anderson (Civil War)|Robert Anderson]] (1805–1871) from [[Fort Sumter]] at the [[Battle of Fort Sumter]] on April 14, 1861.<ref name="jewishcharleston"/><ref name="rosen47"/> In the aftermath of the Civil War, and after his shipping enterprise had been shattered and he became blind, he moved to [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]].<ref name="rosen334">Robert N. Rosen, ''The Jewish Confederates'', Columbia, South Carolina: University of South Carolina Press, 2000, p. 334</ref>

==Personal life==
Mordecai married Isabel Rebecca Lyons (1804-1896).<ref name="rosen40"/> They had four children:
*Hortensia Mordecai (1830-1899)
*Rosa Hays Mordecai Tobias (1832-1897)
*Minnie Mordecai Lazarus (1839-1913)
*Isabel Mordecai (1842-1927)

In 1837, he purchased a mansion in Charleston built for Dr Jean Ernest Poyas (1756-1824) in the [[Adam style]]; it became his family home.<ref name="preservation"/> The house is located at 39 [[Meeting Street]] near [[St. Michael's Episcopal Church (Charleston, South Carolina)|St. Michael's Episcopal Church]], south of [[Broad Street (Charleston, South Carolina)|Broad Street]], in [[Charleston, South Carolina]].<ref name="rosen40"/><ref name="jewishcharleston"/><ref name="rosen9"/> Despite the Civil War, the house still stands today.<ref name="rosen374">Robert N. Rosen, ''The Jewish Confederates'', Columbia, South Carolina: University of South Carolina Press, 2000, p. 374</ref>

==Death==
Mordecai died on December 30, 1888 in Baltimore.

